- L3 Colorists: mastering for Micro-LED walls.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Defines the unique characteristics of Micro-LED (ultra-fast response,
extreme luminance, perfect linearity) that differentiate it from OLED
and LCD. Ensures GIOP ODTs can exploit these capabilities fully.

1. SEMICONDUCTOR MATERIALS
  Micro-LEDs are self-emissive, inorganic light-emitting diodes on a
  silicon or glass backplane.

  Materials:
    Red   : AlInGaP  (Aluminium Indium Gallium Phosphide)
            Peak emission: 630–640 nm
    Green : GaN (Gallium Nitride, with InGaN quantum wells)
            Peak emission: 525–535 nm
    Blue  : GaN (with InGaN quantum wells)
            Peak emission: 450–460 nm

  Inorganic materials provide:
    - No organic degradation → no burn-in, infinite lifetime.
    - Thermal stability → sustained high brightness without cooling.

2. RESPONSE TIME AND MOTION
  Response Time    : < 1 nanosecond (electron-hole recombination)
    This is orders of magnitude faster than OLED (~0.1 ms) and LCD (~1–5 ms).
    The emission turns on/off almost instantaneously.

  Motion Resolution:
    With sub-ns response, the display can achieve true impulse driving
    (like a CRT). Black Frame Insertion at very short duty cycles is
    possible without perceptible flicker. This eliminates sample-and-hold
    blur entirely.
    Equivalent motion resolution: >1000 lines (perfect for 24p cinema
    with no judder or blur).

3. LUMINANCE LINEARITY AND DYNAMIC RANGE
  A key advantage of Micro-LED: the luminance response to drive current
  is perfectly linear from 0.01 cd/m² to over 5000 cd/m². No roll-off,
  no ABL (until thermal limits are reached).

  Peak Luminance (current 2026):
    TV panels       : 4000 cd/m²
    Video walls     : 10,000 cd/m² (achievable with active cooling)
    AR glasses      : 100,000 cd/m² (to overcome ambient sunlight)
  Black Level       : 0 cd/m² (true black, per-pixel turn-off)
  Contrast Ratio    : Infinite
  Dynamic Range     : >20 stops (at 10,000 nit peak)

  For GIOP ODT:
    The PQ EOTF can be mapped directly; the display can reach 10,000 cd/m²
    which is the PQ maximum. This makes Micro-LED the first consumer
    technology to achieve the full PQ range without tone mapping.

4. COLOR PRIMARIES AND GAMUT
  The narrow-band emission of inorganic semiconductors yields very pure
  primaries.

  CIE 1931 xy primaries (typical):
    Red   : (0.708, 0.292)  (Rec.2020 red)
    Green : (0.170, 0.797)  (Rec.2020 green)
    Blue  : (0.131, 0.046)  (Rec.2020 blue)

  Rec.2020 coverage: >95% (nearly complete).
  White Point: D65 (factory calibrated).

  For GIOP: the ODT should target full Rec.2020 primaries. The display's
  internal calibration will map to its native gamut with minimal
  compression.

5. PIXEL PITCH AND SCALABILITY
  Pixel Pitch:
    Consumer TV   : 50–100 μm pitch (e.g., 100" 4K)
    Smartwatch    : 10–20 μm pitch (e.g., 1.5" 300 PPI)
    AR glasses    : <5 μm pitch (e.g., 0.13" full HD)

  Micro-LED panels are assembled from individual LED chips using mass
  transfer technology. The pixel pitch and resolution can be customized
  for any form factor. GIOP stores the pixel pitch and panel dimensions
  in metadata so the ODT knows the native resolution and aspect ratio.

6. GIOP ODT RECOMMENDATION
  Target Primaries  : Rec.2020 (BT.2020), D65 white.
  Target EOTF       : PQ (ST.2084) at 10,000 cd/m² peak (full PQ range).
  Special Considerations:
    - No tone mapping necessary if the content is mastered at 10,000 nits.
    - If mastered at a lower peak (e.g., 1000 nits), the display's
      internal processor can upscale gracefully.
    - For video walls in virtual production: the ODT must include a
      per-panel calibration LUT to uniformize color and luminance across
      the wall.

